Configuration Annotations: @Configuration and @Bean

@Configuration

Marks a class as a source of bean definitions.
Used to define beans using Java code instead of XML.

@Bean

Marks a method as a bean producer. The method’s return value is registered as a bean in the
Spring container.
Example:

@Configuration
public class AppConfig {

    @Bean
    public UserService userService() {
        return new UserService(userRepository());
    }

    @Bean
    public UserRepository userRepository() {
        return new UserRepository();
    }
}

Here, AppConfig is a configuration class.
userService() and userRepository() methods define beans.

When to use:

Use @Configuration and @Bean for explicit, fine-grained control over bean creation, or when
integrating third-party libraries.
